The Vita Field Programmable Gate Array Memory Block has two registers.
The IO register here stores four bits instead of three bits, and the
Single D Flip Flop register stores one bit. The IO register has
twelve valid values that it can have, and those range from 0000 to
1011. When the IO register has the values of 1100 or 1101 or 1110 or
1111, the Memory Block basically becomes a no-op.

When the IO register has the value of 0000, the IONorth pin is the
data input bit of the D Flip Flop and the IOEast pin is the write
enable bit of the D Flip Flop. The IOSouth and IOWest pins are both
continuously assigned the same 1 bit value stored in the D Flip Flop
even when there is no value change. Only when the write enable bit is
the value of 1 and the ClockLine input wire is the value of posedge
does the data input bit become the updated value stored in the D Flip
Flop, and the IOSouth and IOWest pins begin outputting the new value.

When the IO register has the value of 0001, the IOEast pin is the
